      {
        "id": 2220035,
        "name": "Jason Oliver",
        "username": "Jason_Oliver",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/jason_oliver/{size}/2661_2.png",
        "created_at": "2017-07-15T15:57:54.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Jorge Henriquez\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n Jorge Henriquez:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"David Cooper\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n David Cooper:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I spent a week in Livermore in August once and it was scorching so I am going to say A is Livermore.</p>\n<p>Just to be crazy I will say B is St Helena and C is Paso.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I second this one!</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>C is Livermore.  Livermore\u2019s average temp actually is similar to st Helena.  I\u2019ve heard winemakers (familiar with Napa and Livermore) say that Livermore is a cooler climate relative to upper napa valley. I think people have a hot experience in Livermore and maybe get the impression that it is hotter because it gets less precipitation than other areas.  I drink a lot of Napa (and occasional paso), but Livermore is starting to attract talented winemakers in the last several years.  The region is often portrayed as too hot and so I\u2019ve been looking at these weather comparisons lately and that image doesn\u2019t fly.</p>",
